    <prp:abstract>Our deep narrow-band (NB) survey of luminous radio-quiet z~ QSOs gas revealed a spectacular giant Ly-alpha emission nebulae around a QSO, dubbed the Slug. The Ly-alpha halo with a size of ~300 kpc extends well into the IGM, making it the largest such nebulae ever discovered, and likely one of the biggest reservoirs of cool gas known in the high-z Universe. Our narrow-band imaging and follow-up spectroscopy reveals that this system is a proto-clusters, harboring both multiple AGN and significant overdensities of Ly-alpha emitting galaxies. Using deep (20h) PdBI observations, we have detect CO emission from the host galaxy of the QSO, but no emission from the diffuse nebula. Our data indicate that the gas in molecular form is a tiny fraction of the cool gas reservoir in the nebulae. With ALMA, we aim to detect the dust emission associated with the nebulae at high sensitivity (using both a 12m mosaic and ACA imaging given the large 40" extent of the nebula). This benchmark experiment will provide critical insights in the physical properties of some of the most extreme objects found in the distant universe.</prp:abstract>
